\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Confidence intervals.

\series default
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 are all quantities drawn, without replacement, a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

random
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 sample, from some population, the same population, which itself has an
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 distribution.
 If the population size is large enough it's safe to make the approximation
 that each draw does not affect the population distribution (despite non-replace
ment) and so effectively each of the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is a draw from an 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 distribution, i.e.
 each 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is actually the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 What can we say about the distribution of the random variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\equiv\frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_{i}$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 the distribution of the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

sample mean
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

? Furthermore what can we say about the distribution of the sample variance
 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}\equiv\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

?
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Theorem 1.
 
\series default

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

I.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}/n\right)$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

II.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 are independent.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

III.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2}\sim\chi_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

What does this really say? It says that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 is distributed with the same distribution and the 
\series bold
same mean as the population
\series default
 
\series bold
you drew from
\series default
 and that its variance is inversely proportional to the variance of the
 population by a factor equal to the sample size.
 That is to say, if we could somehow figure out the mean of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

, we would then immediately know the mean of the population.
 Of course we can't (philosophically speaking) but we'll do something else
 involving the mean that'll be almost as useful.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\series bold
Proof I.
 
\series default
First we prove that the 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}/n\right)$
\end_inset

: the MGF of 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MGF_{X_{I}}(t)=e^{\mu t+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}t^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

and therefore by the convolution theorem 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
MGF_{X_{1}+\cdots+X_{n}}(t)=\left(e^{\mu t+\frac{1}{2}\sigma^{2}t^{2}}\right)^{n}=e^{\left(\mu n\right)t+\frac{1}{2}\left(\sqrt{n}\sigma\right)^{2}t^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

Hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum X_{i}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(n\mu,n\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Then since the normal distribution is a scale family 
\begin_inset Formula $(1/n)\sum X_{i}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\frac{1}{n}n\mu,\left(\frac{1}{n}\right)^{2}n\sigma^{2}\right)\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}/n\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Let's stop here for a moment see what just this alone buys us.
 Suppose you had some population for which you knew the variance 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 but you didn't know the mean (absurd but suspend disbelief): could you
 make a guess of the mean and then qualify your guess? Well since we know
 that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}/n\right)$
\end_inset

 we know, by 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

standardizing
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(-1.96<\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\grave{\sqrt{\sigma^{2}/n}}}<1.96\right)\geq.95
\]

\end_inset

After a little algebra (and flipping two inequalities) we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(\bar{X}-1.96\sqrt{\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}}<\mu<\bar{X}+1.96\sqrt{\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}}\right)\geq.95
\]

\end_inset

So with probability .95 if we measure 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 the interval
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\bar{X}-1.96\sqrt{\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}},\bar{X}+1.96\sqrt{\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

will cover the true mean of the population (remember we said we somehow
 knew 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 is just the sample size).
 For this reason this is called a 95% confidence interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 This is also called computing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

z test statistic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 since a standard normal random variable is typically represented by a 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Back to the proof of theorem.
\series bold

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Proof II.

\series default
 Note that by location-scale it suffices to prove 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}/n\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 To prove independence of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 we show that they're functions of independent random vectors.
 First we write 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $n-1$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

deviations
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S^{2} & =\frac{1}{n-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\frac{1}{n-1}\left(\left(X_{1}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}+\sum_{i=2}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{n-1}\left(\left[\sum_{i=2}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\right]^{2}+\sum_{i=2}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
Now solve for the quantity
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{1}-\bar{X}\right)$
\end_inset


\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
 using
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
and factor out a
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

 (which gets killed in the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\right]^{2}$
\end_inset

).
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
S^{2}=\frac{1}{n-1}\left(\left[\sum_{i=2}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)\right]^{2}+\sum_{i=2}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset

So 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}=g\left(\left(X_{2}-\bar{X},X_{3}-\bar{X},\dots,X_{n}-\bar{X}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is clearly continuous.
 Now we show that the random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{2}-\bar{X},X_{3}-\bar{X},\dots,X_{n}-\bar{X}\right)$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

, and by continuity 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 will be independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

.
 The joint pdf of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{1},X_{2},\dots,X_{n}\right)$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{X}\left(x_{1},\dots,x_{n}\right) & =\prod_{i=1}^{n}\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}e^{-\frac{1}{2}x_{i}^{2}}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\sum_{i=1}^{n}x_{i}^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now let
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}1/n & 1/n & \cdots & 1/n\\
-1/n & 1-1/n & -1/n & -1/n\\
\vdots & -1/n & \ddots & -1/n\\
-1/n & -1/n & -1/n & 1-1/n
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}\\
x_{2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{n}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}y_{1}\\
y_{2}\\
\vdots\\
y_{n}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
y_{1} & =\bar{x}=\frac{1}{n}x_{1}+\frac{1}{n}x_{2}+\cdots+\frac{1}{n}x_{n}\\
y_{2} & =x_{2}-\bar{x}\\
\vdots & \vdots\\
y_{n} & =x_{n}-\bar{x}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and therefore solve the first equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 by substituting in 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2},x_{3},\dots,x_{n}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{pmatrix}1 & -1 & \cdots & -1\\
1 & 1 & 0 & 0\\
\vdots & 0 & \ddots & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\begin{pmatrix}y_{1}\\
y_{2}\\
\vdots\\
y_{n}
\end{pmatrix}=\begin{pmatrix}x_{1}\\
x_{2}\\
\vdots\\
x_{n}
\end{pmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

Then the Jacobian of the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left|J\right|=\left|\begin{pmatrix}1 & -1 & \cdots & -1\\
1 & 1 & 0 & 0\\
\vdots & 0 & \ddots & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\right|=\left|\begin{pmatrix}n & 0 & \cdots & 0\\
1 & 1 & 0 & 0\\
\vdots & 0 & \ddots & 0\\
1 & 0 & 0 & 1
\end{pmatrix}\right|=n
\]

\end_inset

using the invariance of the determinant under linear combinations of rows.
 Hence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
f_{Y}\left(y_{1},\dots,y_{n}\right) & =f_{X}\left(y_{1}-\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i},y_{1}+y_{2}\dots,y_{1}+y_{n}\right)n\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\left(y_{1}-\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}\right)^{2}+\sum_{i=2}^{n}\left(y_{1}+y_{i}\right)^{2}\right)}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(y_{1}^{2}-2y_{1}\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}+\left(\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}\right)^{2}+\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{1}^{2}+2y_{1}\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}+\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}^{2}\right)}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(y_{1}^{2}+\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{1}^{2}+\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}^{2}+\left(\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}\right)^{2}\right)}\\
 & =\left(\left(\frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi}}\right)^{n}e^{-\frac{1}{2}ny_{1}^{2}}\right)\left(e^{-\frac{1}{2}\left(\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}^{2}+\left(\sum_{i=2}^{n}y_{i}\right)^{2}\right)}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so 
\begin_inset Formula $Y_{1}\equiv\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(Y_{2},Y_{3},\dots,Y_{n}\right)\equiv\left(X_{2}-\bar{X},X_{3}-\bar{X},\dots,X_{n}-\bar{X}\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}=g\left(\left(X_{2}-\bar{X},X_{3}-\bar{X},\dots,X_{n}-\bar{X}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

This is kind of amazing in and of itself, that 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}=h\left(\bar{X}\right)$
\end_inset

 is statistically speaking independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 but it's also useful and why will be apparent after the completion of the
 proof, i.e.
 establishing that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2}\sim\chi_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\family default
\series bold
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
Proof III.
 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
There are two ways to do this.
 First
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}\right)^{2} & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)+\bar{X}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}+2\left(\bar{X}\right)^{2}\cancelto{0}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\bar{X}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\bar{X}\right)^{2}+\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\bar{X}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\left(n-1\right)S^{2}+n\left(\bar{X}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and by almost exactly the same manipulation (the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cross
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 term will be a little different but it's irrelevant since it goes to 0)
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(X_{i}-\mu\right)^{2}=\left(n-1\right)S^{2}+n\left(\bar{X}-\mu\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset

but then (
\family default
\series bold
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
if you're allowed to do this????
\series default
)
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{X_{i}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2} & =\frac{1}{\sigma^{2}}\left(\left(n-1\right)S^{2}+n\left(\bar{X}-\mu\right)^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2}+\left(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Now again by convolution theorem and independence of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
MGF_{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{X_{i}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}} & =MGF_{\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2}}MGF_{\left(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

But 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{X_{i}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}\sim\chi_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}\sim\chi_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\frac{1}{1-2t}\right)^{n/2} & =MGF_{\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2}}\left(\frac{1}{1-2t}\right)^{1/2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
MGF_{\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2}} & =\left(\frac{1}{1-2t}\right)^{n/2}\Bigg/\left(\frac{1}{1-2t}\right)^{1/2}\\
 & =\left(\frac{1}{1-2t}\right)^{\frac{n-1}{2}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and hence 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2}\sim\chi_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 But doesn't this directly imply that 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{X_{i}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n\left(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}$
\end_inset

 doesn't it? 
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit

\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2} & =\frac{1}{\sigma^{2}}\left(\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{X_{i}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}-\left(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}\right)\\
 & =\sum_{i=1}^{n}\left(\frac{X_{i}-\mu}{\sigma}\right)^{2}-n\left(\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The second way is to use induction with 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X_{k}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{k}^{2}$
\end_inset

 being the sample mean and variance for a sample of size 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 The base case
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
S_{2}^{2} & =\frac{1}{2-1}\left(\left(X_{1}-\frac{1}{2}\left(X_{1}+X_{2}\right)\right)^{2}+\left(X_{2}-\frac{1}{2}\left(X_{1}+X_{2}\right)\right)^{2}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\left(X_{1}-X_{2}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and if 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}\sim X_{2}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(\mu,\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}-X_{2}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,2\sigma^{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{1}-X_{2}/\left(\sqrt{2}\sigma\right)\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{\left(2-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S_{2}^{2} & =\frac{1}{2\sigma^{2}}\left(X_{1}-X_{2}\right)^{2}\\
 & =\left(\frac{X_{1}-X_{2}}{\sqrt{2}\sigma}\right)^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

hence 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(2-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S^{2}\sim\chi_{2}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To finish the induction we have to prove that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S_{n}^{2}\sim\chi_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\left(n-2\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S_{n-1}^{2}\sim\chi_{n-2}^{2}$
\end_inset

 (remember the subscript on the 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the subscript necessary for induction).
 Now the induction step requires
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S_{n}^{2}=\frac{\left(n-2\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S_{n-1}^{2}+\left(\frac{n-1}{\sigma^{2}n}\right)\left(X_{n}-\bar{X}_{n-1}\right)^{2}
\]

\end_inset

which is true because of a very length algebraic manipulation.
 Now observe that the random vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(X_{n},\bar{X}_{n-1}\right)$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 since as before 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}_{n-1}$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 is definitely independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 since 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

in the future
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 And finally since 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{n}-\bar{X}_{n-1}\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,n\sigma^{2}/\left(n-1\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 and by the induction hypothesis
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\left(n-1\right)}{\sigma^{2}}S_{n}^{2}=\chi_{n-2}^{2}+\chi_{1}^{2}=\chi_{n-1}^{2}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\blacksquare$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

Now what does 
\family default
\series default
\shape italic
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
this 
\shape default
buy us? Well as mentioned, in general you have no idea what 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma^{2}$
\end_inset

 for a population is so computing 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(\bar{X}-1.96\sqrt{\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}}<\mu<\bar{X}+1.96\sqrt{\frac{\sigma^{2}}{n}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(-1.96<\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\grave{\sqrt{\sigma^{2}/n}}}<1.96\right)
\]

\end_inset

is impossible.
 But what about 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P\left(a<\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\grave{\sqrt{S^{2}/n}}}<b\right)
\]

\end_inset

Well
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T=\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\grave{\sqrt{S^{2}/n}}} & =\frac{\left(\bar{X}-\mu\right)\frac{\sqrt{n}}{\sigma}}{\sqrt{\frac{\left(n-1\right)S^{2}/\sigma^{2}}{\left(n-1\right)}}}=\frac{Z}{\sqrt{V/v}}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $v=n-1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $Z\sim\mathcal{N}\left(0,1\right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $V\sim\chi_{n-1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $Z$
\end_inset

 since yet again 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{X}$
\end_inset

.
 This is the exact form of a Student's t distribution with 
\begin_inset Formula $v=n-1$
\end_inset

 degrees of freedom, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $T\sim T\left(v\right)\sim T\left(n-1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The density is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
f_{T}\left(t\right)=\frac{\Gamma\left(\frac{v+1}{2}\right)}{\sqrt{v\pi}\Gamma\left(\frac{v}{2}\right)}\left(1+\frac{t^{2}}{v}\right)^{-\frac{v+1}{2}}
\]

\end_inset

and so now we can compute 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

t test statistics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 be such that 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(-a<T<a\right)=.90$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P\left(-a<\frac{\bar{X}-\mu}{\grave{\sqrt{S^{2}/n}}}<a\right) & =P\left(\bar{X}-a\sqrt{\frac{S^{2}}{n}}<\mu<\bar{X}-a\sqrt{\frac{S^{2}}{n}}\right)=.90
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so if we draw from our population the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{X}-a\sqrt{\frac{S^{2}}{n}},\bar{X}+a\sqrt{\frac{S^{2}}{n}}\right)$
\end_inset

 will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

cover
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 the true mean with probability .9, i.e.
 it is a 90% confidence interval for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

.
 Quoting wikipedia: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Quotation

\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Therefore, if we find the mean of a set of observations that we can reasonably
 expect to have a normal distribution, we can use the t-distribution to
 examine whether the confidence limits on that mean include some theoretically
 predicted value – such as the value predicted on a null hypothesis.
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

